<subSubSection id="37A86527FB43FFAFEEA6FC8C2575A771" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="7F0D36ACFB43FFAFEEA6FC8C2575A771" blockId="20.[108,637,850,1701]" pageId="20" pageNumber="20">
DIAGNOSIS: 
<taxonomicName id="B8B24D2FFB43FFAFEF30FC8C259DA160" box="[282,395,850,874]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Spinoliella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4DC6EABEFB43FFAFEF30FC8C259DA160" box="[282,395,850,874]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="20">Spinoliella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are most similar to 
<taxonomicName id="B8B24D2FFB43FFAFEE46FCAD2512A181" box="[108,260,883,907]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Callonychium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4DC6EABEFB43FFAFEE46FCAD2512A181" box="[108,260,883,907]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="20">Callonychium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
owing to the subparallel inner margins of the compound eyes and yellow markings on otherwise darker integument. 
<taxonomicName id="B8B24D2FFB43FFAFEC25FC6B266BA1C7" box="[527,637,949,973]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Spinoliella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4DC6EABEFB43FFAFEC25FC6B266BA1C7" box="[527,637,949,973]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="20">Spinoliella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be differentiated from 
<taxonomicName id="B8B24D2FFB43FFAFEFB3FC08263BA1E4" box="[409,557,982,1006]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Callonychium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4DC6EABEFB43FFAFEFB3FC08263BA1E4" box="[409,557,982,1006]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="20">Callonychium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the absence of maculation on the genae (with a longitudinal yellow band in 
<taxonomicName id="B8B24D2FFB43FFAFEFB3FBC62627A63A" box="[409,561,1048,1072]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Callonychium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4DC6EABEFB43FFAFEFB3FBC62627A63A" box="[409,561,1048,1072]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="20">Callonychium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), cleft pretarsal claws in females (simple in 
<taxonomicName id="B8B24D2FFB43FFAFEC23FBE42481A678" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Callonychium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4DC6EABEFB43FFAFEC23FBE42481A678" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="20">Callonychium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and antennal toruli positioned in lower third of face (in lower fourth of face in 
<taxonomicName id="B8B24D2FFB43FFAFEC6CFBA224C3A6BF" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Callonychium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4DC6EABEFB43FFAFEC6CFBA224C3A6BF" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="20">Callonychium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Both genera can be separated from the related genus 
<taxonomicName id="B8B24D2FFB43FFAFEF1BFB6025BEA6DC" authorityName="Brethes" authorityYear="1922" box="[305,424,1214,1238]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Arhysosage" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4DC6EABEFB43FFAFEF1BFB6025BEA6DC" box="[305,424,1214,1238]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="20">Arhysosage</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the presence in the latter genus of ventrally divergent compound eyes, a broad metasoma (wider than mesosoma and sometimes wider than head: see 
<bibRefCitation id="1B234B5DFB43FFAFEC1DFAFF24B3A750" author="Engel, M. S." pageId="20" pageNumber="20" pagination="182 - 208" refId="ref44722" refString="Engel, M. S. 2000. A revision of the panurgine bee genus Arhysosage (Hymenoptera: Andrenidae). Journal of Hymenoptera Research 9 (1): 182 - 208." type="journal article" year="2000">Engel, 2000</bibRefCitation>
), and strongly incurved meso- and metatibial spurs in females.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="37A86527FB43FFAFEEA6FA5A24E9A4AF" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="7F0D36ACFB43FFAFEEA6FA5A24E9A4AF" blockId="20.[108,637,850,1701]" pageId="20" pageNumber="20">
DISTRIBUTION AND FLORAL ASSOCIATIONS: The genus is confined to 
<collectingCountry id="07A5763CFB43FFAFEFBBFA7B2614A7B7" box="[401,514,1445,1469]" name="Argentina" pageId="20" pageNumber="20">Argentina</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="07A5763CFB43FFAFEC6AFA7B266AA7B7" box="[576,636,1445,1469]" name="Chile" pageId="20" pageNumber="20">Chile</collectingCountry>
(tables 1 and 3); individuals of 12 of the known species have been found at a wide variety of flowers (
<tableCitation id="32300317FB43FFAFEEF2F9D62525A42B" box="[216,307,1544,1569]" captionStart="TABLE 4" captionStartId="22.[616,686,225,246]" captionText="TABLE 4 Floral records for species of Spinoliella Ashmead and Xeranthrena Gonzalez and Engel, new genus Records are summarized following the style employed recently by Engel et al. (2017), and cover those newly recorded herein as well as from the literature (see individual species accounts in text). All floral species are eudicots (tricolpates) of the Pentapetalae (Eudicots: Core Eudicots: Pentapetalae), and divided among the “superrosids” (represented here solely by rosids) and “superasterids” (Soltis et al., 2005; Moore et al., 2010). It must be noted that these records do not distinguish between bees collecting pollen versus nectar, and so may not represent pollen host associations. Floral names were checked against the Plant List (2013)." pageId="20" pageNumber="20">table 4</tableCitation>
), although it is unknown whether these were to collect pollen or merely imbibe nectar. Considerable work is needed on the biology of 
<taxonomicName id="B8B24D2FFB43FFAFEF34F9B22587A48E" box="[286,401,1644,1668]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Spinoliella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4DC6EABEFB43FFAFEF34F9B22587A48E" box="[286,401,1644,1668]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="20">Spinoliella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in association with their flowers.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="37A86527FB43FFAFECE6FF3C207BA6D7" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="7F0D36ACFB43FFAFECE6FF3C207BA6D7" blockId="20.[684,1213,226,1245]" pageId="20" pageNumber="20">
COMMENTS: 
<taxonomicName id="B8B24D2FFB43FFAFED76FF3C27DAA2F0" box="[860,972,226,250]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Spinoliella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4DC6EABEFB43FFAFED76FF3C27DAA2F0" box="[860,972,226,250]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="20">Spinoliella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are currently known from 
<collectingCountry id="07A5763CFB43FFAFECC0FEDD2741A311" box="[746,855,259,283]" name="Argentina" pageId="20" pageNumber="20">Argentina</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="07A5763CFB43FFAFEDA5FEDD27DAA311" box="[911,972,259,283]" name="Chile" pageId="20" pageNumber="20">Chile</collectingCountry>
, although at least one species is known from no more than 
<quantity id="B84A9B49FB43FFAFEA58FEFA20ABA336" box="[1138,1213,292,316]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" unit="km" value="35.0">35 km</quantity>
south of the Peruvian border and it is likely that the genus will be found in that country. The genus was revised by 
<bibRefCitation id="1B234B5DFB43FFAFED9DFE5620A1A3AA" author="Toro, H. &amp; L. Ruz" box="[951,1207,391,416]" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" pagination="137 - 171" refId="ref46963" refString="Toro, H., and L. Ruz. 1972 a. Revision del genero Spinoliella (Andrenidae-Apoidea). Anales del Museo de Historia Natural de Valparaiso 5: 137 - 171." type="journal article" year="1972">Toro and Ruz (1972a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="1B234B5DFB43FFAFEC86FE7726E6A3CB" author="Toro, H. &amp; L. Ruz" box="[684,752,425,449]" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" pagination="293 - 295" refId="ref46998" refString="Toro, H., and L. Ruz. 1972 b. Appendice: revision del genero Spinoliella (Andrenidae-Apoidea). Anales del Museo de Historia Natural de Valparaiso 5: 293 - 295." type="journal article" year="1972">1972b</bibRefCitation>
) who initially recognized six species and two subgenera. 
<taxonomicName id="B8B24D2FFB43FFAFED76FE14205FA3E8" box="[860,1097,458,482]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Spinoliella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longirostris">
<emphasis id="4DC6EABEFB43FFAFED76FE14205FA3E8" box="[860,1097,458,482]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="20">Spinoliella longirostris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="B8B24D2FFB43FFAFEA73FE1426F8A009" authorityName="Spinola" authorityYear="1851" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Camptopoeum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nomadoides">
<emphasis id="4DC6EABEFB43FFAFEA73FE1426F8A009" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="20">S. nomadoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="B8B24D2FFB43FFAFED03FE352780A009" box="[809,918,491,515]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Spinoliella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="psamita">
<emphasis id="4DC6EABEFB43FFAFED03FE352780A009" box="[809,918,491,515]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="20">S. psamita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were grouped in the nominate subgenus, while the remaining species were placed in subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="B8B24D2FFB43FFAFEDB6FDF327E4A04F" authorityName="Toro and Ruz. When" authorityYear="1972" box="[924,1010,557,581]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Spinoliella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Peniella">
<emphasis id="4DC6EABEFB43FFAFEDB6FDF327E4A04F" box="[924,1010,557,581]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="20">Peniella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Both subgenera were further characterized by 
<bibRefCitation id="1B234B5DFB43FFAFEA2CFD912094A06D" author="Ruz, L." box="[1030,1154,591,615]" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" pagination="209 - 256" refId="ref46555" refString="Ruz, L. 1991. Classification and phylogenetic relationships of the panurgine bees: the Calliopsini and allies (Hymenoptera: Andrenidae). University of Kansas Science Bulletin 54 (7): 209 - 256." type="journal article" year="1991">Ruz (1991)</bibRefCitation>
and, although they can be recognized on the basis of morphological characters in both sexes, 
<bibRefCitation id="1B234B5DFB43FFAFEC86FD6C274BA0C0" author="Michener, C. D." box="[684,861,690,714]" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" refId="ref45693" refString="Michener, C. D. 2000. The bees of the world. Baltimore: Johns Hopkins University Press, xiv + [i] + 913 pp., + 16 pls." type="book" year="2000">Michener (2000</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="1B234B5DFB43FFAFED43FD6C2789A0C0" author="Michener, C. D." box="[873,927,690,714]" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" refId="ref45728" refString="Michener, C. D. 2007. The bees of the world, 2 nd ed. Baltimore: Johns Hopkins University Press, xvi + [i] + 953 pp., + 20 pls." type="book" year="2007">2007</bibRefCitation>
) considered them unnecessary given the small number of species and that they are not very distinct from each other. Subsequent to 
<bibRefCitation id="1B234B5DFB43FFAFED73FCC82049A124" author="Toro, H. &amp; L. Ruz" box="[857,1119,790,814]" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" pagination="137 - 171" refId="ref46963" refString="Toro, H., and L. Ruz. 1972 a. Revision del genero Spinoliella (Andrenidae-Apoidea). Anales del Museo de Historia Natural de Valparaiso 5: 137 - 171." type="journal article" year="1972">Toro and Ruz’s (1972a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="1B234B5DFB43FFAFEA45FCC820A2A124" author="Toro, H. &amp; L. Ruz" box="[1135,1204,790,814]" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" pagination="293 - 295" refId="ref46998" refString="Toro, H., and L. Ruz. 1972 b. Appendice: revision del genero Spinoliella (Andrenidae-Apoidea). Anales del Museo de Historia Natural de Valparaiso 5: 293 - 295." type="journal article" year="1972">1972b</bibRefCitation>
) account, several species have been described (
<bibRefCitation id="1B234B5DFB43FFAFEC9EFC862724A17A" author="Toro, H." box="[692,818,856,880]" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" pagination="105 - 107" refId="ref46891" refString="Toro, H. 1995. Una nueva especie de Spinoliella (Apoidea: Andrenidae) del norte de Chile. Acta Entomologica Chilena 19: 105 - 107." type="journal article" year="1995">Toro, 1995</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="1B234B5DFB43FFAFED68FC862052A17A" author="Rodriguez, S. &amp; H. Toro &amp; L. Ruz" box="[834,1092,856,880]" pageId="20" pageNumber="20" pagination="99 - 106" refId="ref46276" refString="Rodriguez, S., H. Toro, and L. Ruz. 2001. Dos nuevas especies chilenas del genero Spinoliella (Apoidea: Andrenidae). Revista Chilena de Entomologia 28: 99 - 106." type="journal article" year="2001">Rodríguez et al., 2001</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="1B234B5DFB43FFAFEA7EFC86273AA19B" author="Compagnucci, L. A." pageId="20" pageNumber="20" pagination="77 - 86" refId="ref44598" refString="Compagnucci, L. A. 2015. Revision del genero Spinoliella Ashmead (Apoidea, Andrenidae) en la Argentina, con descripcion de cuatro nuevas especies. Revista del Museo Argentino de Ciencias Naturales 17 (1): 77 - 86." type="journal article" year="2015">Compagnucci, 2015</bibRefCitation>
), bringing the diversity known prior to the present work to a total of 13 species (table 2), although one is newly synonymized herein. Of these additional species, all were ascribed to one of the two subgenera except for the four Argentinean species described by 
<bibRefCitation id="1B234B5DFB43FFAFEA0EFBC126E1A652" author="Compagnucci, L. A." pageId="20" pageNumber="20" pagination="77 - 86" refId="ref44598" refString="Compagnucci, L. A. 2015. Revision del genero Spinoliella Ashmead (Apoidea, Andrenidae) en la Argentina, con descripcion de cuatro nuevas especies. Revista del Museo Argentino de Ciencias Naturales 17 (1): 77 - 86." type="journal article" year="2015">Compagnucci (2015)</bibRefCitation>
, as they appeared to intermingle characters from both subgenera. Although our analysis supported the two subgenera as monophyletic, the distinctions remain minor and we do not advocate their reinstatement at this time.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
